ind trust in disloyal associates, and his harsh treatment of political opponents, Roach suggests that Æthelred has been wrongly maligned. Drawing on extensive research, Roach argues that Æthelred was driven by pious concerns about sin, society, and the anticipated apocalypse. His strategies, in this light, were to honor God and find redemption. Chronologically charting Æthelred's life, Roach presents a more accessible character than previously available, illuminating his place in England and Europe at the turn of the first millennium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Royalty.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300225204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300225204.jpg  a978-3-11-066771-4  YUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO